    <div class="detail-section full ab">
      <div class="slabel">◎ Overview</div>
      <p class="stext" style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.9;">A speaker identification system built in MATLAB using magnitude spectrogram features and minimum-distance scoring. Achieved 100% identification accuracy across 61 test recordings with 16 enrolled speakers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:2px;" class="detail-grid">
    <div class="detail-section ab2">
      <div class="slabel">⊙ System Objective</div>
      <p class="stext">Design a text-independent speaker identification pipeline in MATLAB that extracts spectrogram features from training recordings, builds per-speaker databases, and classifies unknown speakers by minimum-distance scoring against all enrolled databases.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="detail-section">
      <div class="slabel">⊘ Design Constraints</div>
      <div class="spec-list"><div class="spec-item">Feature extraction must be robust to volume differences — column-wise unit-norm normalization required</div><div class="spec-item">DC component must be removed before windowing to prevent low-frequency bias in the spectrogram</div><div class="spec-item">Hamming window of 20 ms with 50% overlap must be consistently applied across all recordings</div><div class="spec-item">Scoring formula: score = sum(min(sqrt(2 - 2*X'*U))) / size(U,2) — must be vectorized for speed</div><div class="spec-item">Output must be automatically saved to uniquely named Excel files per run for reproducibility</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:2px;">
    <div class="detail-section full">
      <div class="slabel">⊞ System Architecture</div>
      <div class="arch-diagram">┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│        SPEAKER RECOGNITION PIPELINE                   │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                       │
│  TRAINING PHASE (recordings 1–3 per speaker)         │
│   <span class="ah">[Audio File]</span> <span class="ah2">──►</span> Remove DC <span class="ah2">──►</span> Hamming Window(20ms)│
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> Magnitude Spectrogram               │
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> Column Normalize (unit norm)        │
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> Concatenate 3 recordings → DB       │
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> Save .mat database file             │
│                                                       │
│  IDENTIFICATION PHASE (remaining recordings)         │
│   <span class="ah">[Unknown Audio]</span> <span class="ah2">──►</span> Same preprocessing pipeline    │
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> Score against ALL speaker DBs       │
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> score = sum(min(√(2−2·X'·U)))/N    │
│               <span class="ah2">──►</span> Argmin score → Predicted Speaker    │
│                                                       │
│  EVALUATION                                          │
│   Confusion Matrix + Excel Score Sheet               │
│                                                       │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:2px;" class="detail-grid">
    <div class="detail-section ab3">
      <div class="slabel">⊛ Software Architecture</div>
      <p class="stext">The MATLAB pipeline consists of two phases. In training, the first three recordings per speaker have their DC mean subtracted, then a short-time magnitude spectrogram is computed using a 20 ms Hamming window at 50% overlap. Each spectrogram column is normalized to unit L2-norm to remove gain variation. The three matrices are concatenated and saved as a .mat speaker database. In identification, remaining recordings are processed through the identical pipeline. Each unknown matrix U is scored against every database X using score = sum(min(sqrt(2 - 2*X'*U))) / size(U,2) — the mean of per-frame minimum cosine distances. The lowest score is the predicted speaker. All scores and predictions are written to a uniquely named Excel file and a confusion matrix is generated.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="detail-section abg">
      <div class="slabel">◈ Correctness &amp; Validation</div>
      <p class="stext">This is a batch offline DSP system, not a real-time control system. The pipeline is fully deterministic given fixed recordings: the same input always produces the same score and prediction. Processing time is bounded by recording length and speaker count. No random state, no order-dependent behavior.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
